Pre-heat your oven to 220 degrees. Wash the @Sweet Potato{2} then chop lengthways
into wedges the thickness of your index finger. Toss in @olive oil{2%tbsp} and
half the @Garlic Salt{2} (save half for later), then spread in a single layer on
a #baking tray{}. Cook on the top shelf of your #oven{} until crispy (around
~{25%mins}).

In a #bowl{} mix together the @British Beef Mince{500%g} with the remaining
garlic salt, half the @Ketchup{2} (save half for later) and a few grinds of
@black pepper{}.

Divide the mixture into four equal portions and then gently form into burger
patties roughly 1 1/2 cm thick.

> Tip: It is important that you press the meat together firmly enough to make it
> stick, yet not so firmly that it becomes densely packed, as this will give a
> tough texture.

Once the potatoes are almost ready, split the @Brioche Bun{4} in half. Put a
#frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Toast the buns for ~{2%mins} on each side then
remove.

> Tip: You could use your toaster but whatever happens don't let them burn!

In the same frying pan heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} on medium-high heat. Once hot,
gently add in the patties and cook for ~{3-4%mins} on each side, turning only
once.

> Tip: We love dribble-down-your-chin medium/rare which takes around 3 mins on each
> side but cook them for a little longer if you like.

Whilst you are cooking the second side of the burger, grate the @Smoked Cheese{4}
on top (of the cooked side!) for the last minute so that it melts. Thinly slice
the @Vine Tomatoes{2}.

Toss the @Wild Rocket{2} in a little drizzle of @olive oil{} with a small pinch
of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Spread a little of the remaining ketchup on the toasted burger buns. Place the
burger on top then lay the tomato and rocket on top and serve with your rustic
chips on the side.

> Tip: You can serve any remaining tomatoes and rocket on the side too.